\par
(This function handles gradual color filter changes on the screen. The way it works is, SNES register $2132 receives color data in a specific format; the bottom 5 bits are for intensity between 0 and 31, and the top 3 bits specify which of the aspects of the color - red, green, blue, or some combination thereof - should be set to that intensity, allowing for 32,768 colors in total. The top bit of $44 determines whether the intensity is increasing or decreasing, and the rest of $44 determines the degree of change. $46 contains the current intensity in its top 5 bits; the other 3 bits are for the "fractional" part of the intensity. If we're decreasing intensity, the change stops at 0; if we're increasing intensity, the change stops at whatever value is specified in the bottom 5 bits of $4C. The top 3 bits of $4C specify the combination of RGB values being affected as previously described.)\par
